english:
  title: A Memorial Against the Relocation of the Capital
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your servant humbly submits that in governing a realm, the welfare of the people must be the foundation, and in ensuring their welfare, the sufficiency of grain must come first. When grain is insufficient, the people inevitably suffer hardship; when the people suffer, resentment deepens, and the realm itself faces peril. Therefore, the sage-kings of old undertook all their great works for the sake of the people. When King Pangeng moved the Shang capital, it was because the common folk faced drowning in the Yellow River's floods and the agony of displacement. When the Grand King moved to Qi, it was because the Di people invaded—he could not allow the land meant to nurture his subjects to become a source of their harm.

    Our nation's capital at Hanseong was established by the Former King and is where our ancestral shrine and altar of the state reside. Ordinarily, it should remain where it is to stabilize the people's hearts. Yet Your Highness has reigned seven years without moving, because the people, content with their ancient home, desired no relocation—so you honored their will. Last year, when someone petitioned for the move, you personally announced the date before the ancestral shrine. The relocation is thus decided and beyond further debate. Yet we must consider that fortune and misfortune attend different seasons, and affairs have their proper timing and urgency.

    This year's drought far exceeds any in recent memory. The people's harvest amounts to but one or two in ten. The common folk are anxious, knowing not where their next meal will come. All other works should cease; we should console them, teaching frugality and food storage, all efforts bent toward staving off famine—gathering wild fruits, promoting trade in such goods. Yet now, when every hand is needed, when the crisis is as pressing as fire spreading to one's own hair, the entire realm undertakes migration. The people exhaust themselves in travel and construction, squandering what little grain remains, leaving no time for other provisions. The wealthy might barely survive the coming winter, but the poor will perish from hunger before winter's end. It is as though one tended a gravely ill patient, denying them rest and care, and instead administered poison to hasten their death. No one with a compassionate heart could bear to witness this. To rescue the starving is the urgent task of this year; relocation is not advantageous for this year.

    Moreover, among the people, only those able to erect even a simple shelter can cover their own bodies, while the servants and slaves have nothing to shield them—all exposed to wind, frost, ice, and snow. If slaves suffer thus, what of the cattle and horses? Though mere beasts, they too have feeling. This year's poor harvest leaves fodder scarce; coupled with the strain of relocation, their suffering multiplies a hundredfold. Their hunger, cold, and anguish—are these not akin to human suffering? Considering this, the tens of millions of lives—human and animal alike—condemned to starve and freeze in misery and resentment, are beyond counting.

    The benevolent rulers of old, seeing one subject shiver, would say, "I have caused this chill." Seeing one hunger, they would say, "I have caused this hunger." When even one person could not find their proper place, they felt as though they had thrust that person into a ditch themselves. How then can you consign tens of millions to starvation and cold without concern? Their grief and resentment will not scatter elsewhere—they will gather upon Your Highness alone. Your servant's heart grieves deeply. Should not the order to relocate be suspended, awaiting a year of abundance? What harm in delay?

    Some may say this year favors relocation, while the next one or two years do not. Yet if the coming years prove unfavorable, must there not eventually come a fortunate year? You have already foregone relocation for six or seven years to honor the people's wishes; to refrain for two or three more years due to their hardship seems no great failure. Your Highness is the parent of the people; the people are the root of the realm. When the root withers, can the branches alone flourish? When children freeze and starve, can the parents' hearts know peace?

    To press forward with relocation this year for its supposed auspiciousness, heedless of the people's hunger, seems to your servant unwise. Some might say: how can we know that Heaven's drought is not itself a sign against relocation? Yet consider: the command to relocate was fixed last winter. Before that decision was made, no such bitter drought existed. Only after the relocation was decided did this terrible drought arrive. Can this truly be Heaven's sign against postponement? Had Heaven truly favored relocation, surely this year would have brought abundance, not famine.

    Heaven's will is difficult to discern, but human suffering is plain to see. To align with Heaven's way, one must follow the people's will. Your servant reverently urges: fear Heaven's calamity above, take pity on the people's plight below. Suspend the relocation order for now. Sustain the hungry masses while awaiting a more auspicious year. Thus will the people find great fortune, and the realm find great fortune.
